<TITLE> New treaty same as EU constitution: UK report </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Jan 20 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Key parts of the Lisbon Treaty that Prime Minister Gordon Brown signed last month are the same as the rejected European Union constitution, according to a British parliamentary report published on Sunday. The report's findings are problematic as the government had promised a referendum on the constitution before it was abandoned, while the Lisbon Treaty needs only parliamentary approval. Parliament begins debate on the treaty on Monday. The report by the House of Commons Foreign Affairs Committee found that the framework for foreign policy laid out in the treaty was no different from that in the constitution. It also accused the government of being less than clear with voters about the importance of some new EU institutions created under the treaty, including a foreign minister's post. "We conclude that there is no material difference between the provisions on foreign affairs in the Constitutional Treaty which the government made subject to approval in a referendum and those in the Lisbon Treaty on which a referendum is being denied," the bi-partisan committee concluded. It went on to state: "We are concerned that the government risks underestimating, and certainly is downplaying in public, the importance and potential of the new foreign policy institutions established by the Lisbon Treaty. "We recommend that the government should publicly acknowledge the significance of the foreign policy aspects of the Lisbon Treaty." Speaking to the BBC, Foreign Minister David Miliband, who says the treaty does not need to go to a referendum as it is not constitutional and does not involve a loss of sovereignty, again defended the government's decision. "The reform treaty is there for parliament to scrutinise and then to pass," he said. "Obviously people will put down an amendment and parliament will have to decide. But I don't believe that this treaty meets the bar of fundamental constitutional reform that should be the basis of having a referendum." Brown signed the Lisbon Treaty in mid-December along with the other EU heads of state and government. It now has to be ratified by EU parliaments before coming into force. The treaty was drawn up after voters in France and the Netherlands resoundingly rejected the EU constitution in referendums. In 2005, former prime minister Tony Blair had promised a referendum on the proposed constituti
